  "prompt": "Why are Hela cells immortal?",
  "response": "HeLa cells are considered \"immortal\" because they can divide indefinitely in culture. This unique characteristic is due to several factors:\n\n1. **Telomerase Activity**: HeLa cells have high levels of telomerase, an enzyme that adds telomeres to the ends of chromosomes. Telomeres typically shorten with each cell division, eventually leading to cell senescence or death. The presence of telomerase allows HeLa cells to maintain their telomeres, enabling continuous division.\n\n2. **Genetic Mutations**: HeLa cells contain numerous genetic mutations, including those that affect cell cycle regulation and apoptosis (programmed cell death). These mutations allow the cells to bypass normal checkpoints that would otherwise limit their proliferation.\n\n3. **Robust Growth**: HeLa cells grow robustly in laboratory conditions, making them easy to culture and maintain over long periods.\n\n4. **Adaptability**: They are highly adaptable and can survive in various environments, contributing to their ability to proliferate indefinitely.\n\nThese factors combined make HeLa cells an invaluable tool in medical research, though their aggressive growth also means they can contaminate other cell cultures if not handled carefully.",
